# Browser Injection Standards

## Content Validation
Validate all content being injected into browser contexts for security and compatibility.

### Security Checks
- **No template literals**: Avoid template literals in injected scripts as they can introduce XSS vulnerabilities
- **No Unicode characters**: Use escaped sequences or avoid Unicode in injected JavaScript
- **ES module compatibility**: Ensure injected scripts work in browser environments
- **Input sanitization**: Validate and sanitize all dynamic content before injection

### Code Quality
- **Strict TypeScript**: Use TypeScript strict mode for all injection scripts
- **Error handling**: Include proper try-catch blocks and error reporting
- **Performance**: Minimize script size and execution time
- **Compatibility**: Test across target browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari)

## Injection Patterns
```typescript
// 👍 Good - static, validated content
const script = `
  (function() {
    const button = document.querySelector('[data-automation-id="submit"]');
    if (button) {
      button.addEventListener('click', function() {
        console.log('Button clicked');
      });
    }
  })();
`;

// 👎 Avoid - template literals with dynamic content
const script = `
  (function() {
    const selector = '${dynamicSelector}'; // XSS vulnerability
    document.querySelector(selector);
  })();
`;
```

## Validation Checklist
- [ ] No template literals in injected scripts
- [ ] No Unicode characters that could cause encoding issues
- [ ] Scripts tested in target browser environments
- [ ] Error handling included for runtime failures
- [ ] Content properly escaped and sanitized
- [ ] Scripts follow CSP (Content Security Policy) requirements